<hr>



<p>While this may sound pretty easy, the amount of information that can be returned to you can be huge and overwhelming. If you enter the term "cat" into Google, what are returned are over 2 billion results in less than one second, see the example below:</p>


<img class="img-wrap style1" src="images/internet/googlesearch.png" alt="">
<hr>														<p>The amount of information and time for search is circled in the picture. Notice the categories of information, highlighted in the left panel. You can narrow your search by clicking on one of these categories such as images, maps, videos, news, or shopping. </p>

<hr>							<p>Each search engine contains a database of sites and when you search with the engine, you are searching the database, not the entire Internet. You will receive a different set of sites even with the same search criteria if you utilize more than one search engine. It is a good idea to explore multiple search engines because each search engine leads you to only a fraction of the entire Internet.</p>
							<p>Many search engines also display sponsored sites first before they display the results of the search. Sponsored sites are sites that have paid a fee to be listed first or in a priority position. WATCH FOR THIS!</p>
